  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published by Peter Lang Verlag in 2018, <em>Competition, Community, and Educational Growth</em> by Kristopher Copeland and Garret L. Castleberry occupies a focused niche at the intersection of competitive forensics, public speaking pedagogy, and educational development. The book has accumulated two formal citations and maintains a presence in commercial retail channels, with library holdings confirming its availability to practitioners and researchers in the forensics and argumentation community.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book's scholarly footprint, while modest in raw citation count, is meaningful in context. Both citations appear in <em>Argumentation and Advocacy</em>, a peer-reviewed journal dedicated to the study of debate and public discourse, and both were recorded in consecutive years (2020 and 2021), suggesting that the work entered active circulation within its specialist community relatively soon after publication. Notably, co-author Kristopher Copeland is among the citing authors, indicating that the book has served as a foundation for his own subsequent research agenda \u2014 a pattern not uncommon in specialist monographs that carve out new conceptual ground within a defined scholarly community.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The institutional profile of the citing works further contextualizes the book's reach: affiliations include Tulsa Community College and the University of Oklahoma, pointing to engagement at both two-year and research university settings. This breadth suggests the volume resonates with educators working across different institutional contexts, consistent with its subject matter of educational growth through competitive academic activity. The thematic concentration on competitor analysis and psychological dimensions of forensics in the citing literature reflects the book's apparent emphasis on how competitive environments shape learning and community formation.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Library cataloguing offers an additional signal of the book's intended audience and pedagogical utility. WorldCat subject headings \u2014 covering debates and debating, public speaking, forensics, and their study and teaching \u2014 align the volume squarely with programs that train students in competitive speech and argumentation. With holdings recorded across at least five library collections, the book has achieved a baseline of institutional acquisition consistent with a specialized academic monograph. Its presence on commercial platforms such as Amazon and Goodreads further indicates that it has been made accessible beyond traditional library channels, broadening potential readership to coaches, graduate students, and independent practitioners.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Taken together, the available evidence positions <em>Competition, Community, and Educational Growth</em> as a specialist contribution to forensics education scholarship \u2014 one whose influence, at this stage, is concentrated within a tight but engaged disciplinary community. Its citation percentile rank, which places it in approximately the 77th percentile among comparable works, suggests it is performing creditably relative to its peer set, even if broader cross-disciplinary uptake has yet to materialize. For researchers and educators working at the nexus of competitive debate and educational theory, the volume represents a grounded reference point with demonstrated staying power in its core field.</p>",
